TY  - JOUR
T1  - Training Programs for Performance Appraisal: A Review
AU  - Smith, David E.
Y1  - 1986/01/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4282615
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4282615
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 22
EP  - 40
VL  - 11
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Twenty-four studies that have researched the effects of rater training on the psychometric quality of performance ratings are reviewed. For comparison, training methods are categorized by (a) content of training; and (b) method used to present training. The results suggest that the most widely used rater training approach is inappropriate for improving rating accuracy. These findings are discussed in terms of Borman's Model of Performance Appraisal (Borman, 1978). Training programs that improve rating accuracy are identified.
AB  - Twenty-four studies that have researched the effects of rater training on the psychometric quality of performance ratings are reviewed. For comparison, training methods are categorized by (a) content of training; and (b) method used to present training. The results suggest that the most widely used rater training approach is inappropriate for improving rating accuracy. These findings are discussed in terms of Borman's Model of Performance Appraisal (Borman, 1978). Training programs that improve rating accuracy are identified.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4282615
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1986.4282615
