TY  - JOUR
T1  - The First-Line Supervisor: Phasing Out or Here To Stay?
AU  - Kerr, Steven
AU  - Hill, Kenneth D.
AU  - Broedling, Laurie
Y1  - 1986/01/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4282635
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4282635
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 103
EP  - 117
VL  - 11
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The literature on first-line supervisors was reviewed to gain an under-standing of their position. There has been a significant loss of autonomy as external influences have eroded first-line supervisory power. Activities of the first-line supervisor and a table of leader behaviors associated with subordinate performance and attitudes are presented. The likely impacts of (a) growth of participative management, (b) increased use of autonomous work groups, (c) use of computers in management, and (d) influence of staff specialists, are discussed.
AB  - The literature on first-line supervisors was reviewed to gain an under-standing of their position. There has been a significant loss of autonomy as external influences have eroded first-line supervisory power. Activities of the first-line supervisor and a table of leader behaviors associated with subordinate performance and attitudes are presented. The likely impacts of (a) growth of participative management, (b) increased use of autonomous work groups, (c) use of computers in management, and (d) influence of staff specialists, are discussed.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4282635
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1986.4282635
