TY  - JOUR
T1  - Moderator Variables in Leadership Research
AU  - Howell, Jon P.
AU  - Dorfman, Peter W.
AU  - Kerr, Steven
Y1  - 1986/01/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4282632
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4282632
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 88
EP  - 102
VL  - 11
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Much recent research on leadership has concerned moderator (contingency) variables. This research has yielded equivocal and/or conflicting results. Conceptually distinct variables have been treated as if they operate in the same fashion. This paper suggests a typology of moderators based on the mechanisms by which moderators operate. Moderators are classified as neutralizers/enhancers, substitutes/supplements, or mediators depending on how they affect leader behavior-criterion relationships. The typology is applied to several contingency theories of leadership and implications for future leadership research and practice are discussed.
AB  - Much recent research on leadership has concerned moderator (contingency) variables. This research has yielded equivocal and/or conflicting results. Conceptually distinct variables have been treated as if they operate in the same fashion. This paper suggests a typology of moderators based on the mechanisms by which moderators operate. Moderators are classified as neutralizers/enhancers, substitutes/supplements, or mediators depending on how they affect leader behavior-criterion relationships. The typology is applied to several contingency theories of leadership and implications for future leadership research and practice are discussed.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4282632
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1986.4282632
Y2  - 2026/04/24
