TY  - JOUR
T1  - Development and Application of a Model of Personal Control in Organizations
AU  - Greenberger, David B.
AU  - Strasser, Stephen
Y1  - 1986/01/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1986.4282657
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1986.4282657
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 164
EP  - 177
VL  - 11
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A dynamic model of personal control is proposed in this paper. Personal control is defined as the individual's beliefs, at a given point in time, in his or her ability to effect a change, in a desired direction, on the environment. Individuals in organizations are viewed as desirous of increasing their personal control. It is argued that employees of organizations persist in their attempts to restore a balance in their control perceptions, even when desired outcomes may not be attainable. Managerial implications of the model are described.
AB  - A dynamic model of personal control is proposed in this paper. Personal control is defined as the individual's beliefs, at a given point in time, in his or her ability to effect a change, in a desired direction, on the environment. Individuals in organizations are viewed as desirous of increasing their personal control. It is argued that employees of organizations persist in their attempts to restore a balance in their control perceptions, even when desired outcomes may not be attainable. Managerial implications of the model are described.
